Panic threshold
Copenhagen - we often hear that the world we know will face its end in an apocalyptic manner, commonly described as an ecological collapse.
In fact, since the Club of Rome published its seminal work "The Limits to Growth" more than forty years ago, its fundamental idea has been accompanying us.
But time is not lenient.
In 1972, "The Limits to Growth" warned humanity that a disastrous collapse was near at hand.
However, we have seen financial panics but no genuine shortages or production collapse.
However, human ingenuity has created a surplus of resources to satisfy human consumption.
However, the fundamental idea of "The Limits to Growth" still holds true: we continue a trend, getting entangled in misleading solutions to trivial issues while ignoring the big problems and wise solutions.
In the early 1970s, the optimism of technological progress was over, the Vietnam War became a disaster, society plunged into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson's 1962 book "Silent Spring" ignited public alarm over pollution and sparked the modern environmental movement; Paul Ehrlich's 1968 title "The Population Bomb" spelled it all out.
On the first Earth Day in 1970, people were filled with pessimism.
The intention of "The Limits to Growth" was to alarm people about the depletion of resources.
This is our fate, because too many people want to consume too much.
Even though our ingenuity buys us some time, we will ultimately destroy the Earth and ourselves with pollution.
The only hope is to achieve stable society at a significantly lower level of poverty than now by stagnating economic growth itself, reducing consumption, recycling, and forcing people to have fewer children.
This perspective still resonates today, despite being grossly misguided.
For example, the authors of "The Limits to Growth" predicted that the world would exhaust aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc before 2013.
However, even though commodity prices have recently rebounded, they have overall fallen to one-third of their levels 150 years ago.
Technological innovation has replaced mercury in batteries, dental fillings, and thermometers, and mercury consumption has plummeted by 98% and prices have dropped by 90% since 2000.
More broadly, since 1946, copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc supply have all exceeded demand, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and the advent of more economical extraction technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were originally predicted to be depleted by 1990 and 1992, respectively; today, reserves of both exceed their 1970 levels, despite our greatly increased consumption.
In the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled the potential natural gas reserves in the United States and halved the price.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP will increase 14-fold this century, with developing countries increasing 24-fold.
The authors of "The Limits to Growth" were mistaken because they overlooked the greatest resource of all: our own ingenuity.
Population growth has been slowing down since the 1960s.
Grain supplies have not collapsed (15 billion hectares of arable land are being used, and in addition, there are 27 billion hectares in reserve).
Malnutrition rates have been reduced by more than half, from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
Pollution has not posed a problem for us.
The Club of Rome imagined a tranquil past where we had no suspended particulate air pollution, were all happy farmers, and in the future, chimney stacks from heating would make us unable to breathe. Reality is entirely at odds with this.
In 1900, the global population was just 1.5 billion, yet nearly 3 million people – approximately one in every 500 – died each year from air pollution, mostly indoor air pollution.
By now, this ratio has dropped to one death in every 2,000 people.
Although the mortality rate from pollution is still higher than that from malaria, it has been decreasing rather than increasing.
Despite this, the ideas cultivated in "The Limits to Growth" still influence the thinking of the public and the elite.
Let's take recycling as an example. It's often just a feel-good gesture that's expensive for the environment with minimal effect.
For example, paper typically comes from sustainably managed forests rather than tropical rainforests.
The programs and government subsidies related to paper recycling bring low-quality paper, and they protect resources that are not under threat.
Similarly, policies fearing overpopulation leading to self-destruction, such as China's one-child policy and India's forced sterilization, have been implemented.
In addition, although pesticides and other pollutants were thought to be capable of killing half of humanity, good pesticide regulation has resulted in only 20 annual deaths in the US, while pesticide use has created more affordable and abundant food supplies.
In fact, relying solely on organic farming – a movement spurred by pesticide hysteria – would impose an additional $100 billion in annual costs on the United States.
Agricultural efficiency would decline by 16%, requiring 65 million additional hectares of land to be cultivated to maintain current output – half the size of modern-day California.
Price increases would lead to a decrease in the consumption of fruits and vegetables, resulting in severe negative health effects (including tens of thousands of additional cancer deaths per year).
Obsessing over dark scenarios prevents us from focusing on the real global threats.
Poverty is one of the biggest killers, and yet 15 million people still die from easily treatable diseases each year - equivalent to a quarter of all deaths.
The solution lies in economic growth.
When people are lifted out of poverty, most can afford the costs of preventing infectious diseases.
In the past thirty years, China has lifted 680 million people out of poverty, leading the world in reducing the number of people living in poverty by nearly a billion.
This has brought about significant improvements in health, lifespan, and quality of life.
Forty years of history since the publication of "The Limits to Growth" have shown that we need more, not less, growth.
Trade expansion is estimated to bring in more than $100 trillion in annual benefits by the end of the century, far surpassing the meager benefits of the timid "feel-good" policies driven by fear.
But this requires abandoning the anti-growth mindset and unleashing our boundless potential to create a brighter future.
